    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start for the intro. Some of my students are pretty sharp and might ask why some legal scholars and judges actually hate the idea of substantive due process or think it's problematic. Could you write up a summary of the main legal arguments used against it? I want to make sure I can present the critique fairly.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Critics of substantive due process often argue it is vague and overly judicial, allowing judges to impose their personal policy preferences rather than strictly interpreting the Constitution's text. Many legal scholars contend that it lacks clear boundaries, leading to inconsistent application across different court cases. Furthermore, some argue that this doctrine improperly elevates unenumerated rights, effectively granting the courts the power to \"find\" rights that the founders never explicitly secured.",
      "source": "target",
